# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A referendum on the constitution of the Batavian Republic was held on August 8, 1797.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The draft constitution was rejected, eventually culminating in a coup d'état.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Following the French Revolution, the Patriots brought an end to the rule of stadtholder William V in the Dutch Republic, with support from the French army.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] They proclaimed the Batavian Republic, and established the National Assembly to draft a constitution, which would be put to a referendum.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Its members disagreed about the extent of suffrage and about whether to organise the republic as a federal or unitary state.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The Patriots had originally supported a federal state with autonomy for the provinces, but some wanted to emulate the unitary model of the French First Republic with a strong central government.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] After two years of debate, a draft constitution with compromises was completed on May 10, 1797.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The draft constitution had been rejected by almost eighty percent, which meant that a new Constitution would have to be drafted.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] In the elections for the National Assembly a few months later, the supporters of a unitary state won the majority, but the supporters of a federal state retained the majority in the constitutional commission.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Meanwhile, in France, the radicals led by Pierre Augereau had seized power.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] With French help, the radical unitarists staged a coup d'état in January 1798.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A new draft constitution, establishing a unitary republic, was quickly adopted in the National Assembly.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1797-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The Constitution for the Batavian People was approved in a referendum on April 23, 1798.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Batavian Republic on 23 April 1798, approving the Constitution for the Batavian People.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] They proclaimed the Batavian Republic, and established the National Assembly to draft a constitution.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A compromised constitution was rejected by the electorate in an August 1797 referendum.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] On 22 January 1798, a coup d'état was carried out by those favouring a unitary state with the support of the French, who were dissatisfied with the referendum result and prolonged debates.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The remaining members of the National Assembly finished drafting the Constitution for the Batavian People two months later.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Voters were asked on 21 April 1798 to approve the Constitution for the Batavian People.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] An overwhelming majority voted in favour, but only those who swore allegiance to the coup were allowed to vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] After the referendum, another coup d'état was carried out by the Unitarians, and the constitution became effective in July 1798.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1798-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The French, who had a major influence on the Batavian Republic, were not satisfied with the 1798 constitution, so a new constitution was written, for which a referendum in 1801 was organized.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Batavian Republic on 6 October 1801.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] After a previous referendum in 1798 resulted in a new constitution being approved, the French were not satisfied with this constitution, and under their influence a new constitution was written.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] In 1801, a referendum was held about the new constitution.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Non-voters were counted as if they agreed to the new constitution, and the constitution passed with 87.46% in favour.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1801-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] On 16 October 1801, the new constitution became official.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Batavian Republic between 9 and 16 April 1805.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Although a new constitution had been approved in an 1801 referendums, the French authorities put pressure on the Batavian State Council to pass a new constitution in which executive power was held by a single person, the Grand pensionary, a post initially filled by Rutger Jan Schimmelpenninck.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution had 87 articles, which provided for a 19-seat Parliament with a three-year term which could pass or reject bills, but not change them.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Voting was not secret and took place by signing registers at meetings, meaning invalid votes were not possible.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] Voters had the option to vote for, against or abstain, with abstentions counted as a "for" vote.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1805-batavian-republic-constitutional-referendum] As a result, the constitution was approved by 99.96% of voters.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 30 November and 4 December 1848.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] Held immediately after the Constitutional Reform of 1848, they were the first direct elections to the House of Representatives, and were the first to elect a States General to which government ministers would be responsible.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] Voting was restricted to men over the age of 23, and who paid a certain level of taxation.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] This limited the franchise to 55,728 people, roughly 11% of the male population over 23, or 2.5% of the total population of the country.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] Candidates were elected in districts in a two-round system; if no candidate received over 50% of the vote in the first round, the top two candidates would face a run-off.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] The districts had one MP for every 45,000 inhabitants.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1848-dutch-general-election] As there were no official political parties until 1879, all candidates were nominally independents.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1850-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 27 August 1850.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] General elections were held in the Netherlands on 17 May 1853.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] They followed the dissolution of the House of Representatives as a result of a government crisis caused by the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] The result of the elections was a defeat for Prime Minister Johan Rudolph Thorbecke and his liberals.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] Only the province of Groningen and Twente remained a liberal stronghold.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] The conservative Van Hall-Donker Curtius cabinet thus received ample support in the House of Representatives and Floris Adriaan van Hall became prime minister.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] However, the restoration of the episcopal hierarchy that had caused the government crisis was not reversed, although the Roman Catholic Church was restricted in its freedom of movement by the introduction of the Law on Church Societies.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] During the Constitutional Reform of 1848, the Catholic Church was allowed to determine ecclesiastical divisions within the Netherlands in the context of the separation of church and state.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] In 1853 this law was applied, and Pope Pius IX divided the Netherlands into five dioceses, including an archdiocese in Utrecht.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] Among the Dutch Protestants, there was much dislike of this action, which culminated in the April movement.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] The submission of the complaints by the April movement to King William III led to a crisis between the king and the Thorbecke I cabinet, which felt that the king had answered the April movement too positively and had not been sufficiently neutral.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] As a result, the cabinet resigned and the House of Representatives was dissolved.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1853-dutch-general-election] According to the electoral law in force at the time, this was an exceptional situation: normally half the House was elected every two years, and not the House as a whole.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] An election for Members of the European Parliament representing Netherlands constituency for the 1989–1994 term of the European Parliament was held on 15 June 1989.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] It was part of the wider 1989 European election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Ten parties competed in a D'Hondt type election for 25 seats.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Several parties combined in one list to take part in this European Election and increase their chance on a seat in the European Parliament.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] All Dutch, everywhere in the world were granted voting rights this election.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Except for the Dutch living in the Netherlands Antilles and Aruba, because they can vote for the Estates of the Netherlands Antilles.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] However, if the subject lived for 10 years or longer in the Netherlands they can still vote for the European Elections.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] In the election the conservative liberal VVD loses seats to the progressive liberal D66, who return to the European parliament after a five-year absence.
[src:1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands/1989-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] 47.48% of the Dutch population turned out on election day.
